<br>
And <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>never</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  You tell Bard01, 'We need more mana, how fast can you sing?'</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Wezloc:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Reason being ask a cleric what class they want to group with if they had to pick? A enchanter with KEI or a Mage with Mod Rods...I am willing to bet 9 out of 10 will say Enchanter.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->And I'd bet you're wrong.  Clerics are among the best partners for mages, and mages are among the best partners for clerics.  You did know that clerics healing elementals generates no aggro, didn't you?  That a cleric can cast a complete heal on trusty <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Gobaner</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> (as opposed to that treasonous agitator Lobaner), and sit right back down on their butts and get no aggro?  Even if there are four mobs on the pet?<br>
<br>
Take a look at the response to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/forums/showthread.php?s=&amp;threadid=11842">Mages invite clerics to group</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Wezloc:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  T-Rods are nice to have but not needed in a group setting.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Well, rods are only needed if you want to live up to your DPS potential as a mage.  If you feel like slacking off, go right ahead.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Wezloc:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  so IMO that hardly makes this spell second most powerful in the game when it is only needed for 5% of all the content in the game.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Maybe you're not making the best possible use of your spells.  I for one have a spell slot dedicated to T-Rods, which is only unmemmed when I find myself suddenly naked at bind point.  It is also the first spell I mem, and the first spell I cast every time I log on.  Clearly the most profound spell for mages in all of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Luclin</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Immlazen:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  ...but my ability I believe comes from me killing whatever and keeping my pet alive.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I believe my strength comes from my right hand, and therefore it should never be necessary to fight with my left hand.<br>
<br>
What is so sacred about 1 pet, N nukes, and K heals?  Nothing.<br>
I could just as well argue that I should never need to cast more than 1 nuke, and always be able to make up the difference by casting more pets.  While a perfectly valid tactic, it would be idiotic to claim that it is the only legitimate tactic for mages, and demand that the class be balanced around that style of play alone, and in particular, to demand capabilities to make up for the inherit weakness in that one tactic.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Immlazen:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  YOU SUMMON A PET. BUFF YOUR PET UP. GIVE YOU PET ARMOR AND WEAPONS. SEND HIM OFF TO FIGHT. HE GETS LOW ON HP AND YOU HEAL HIM COMPLETELY.<br>
<br>
Now how is that Nerfing?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Please tell the beastlords that you want a better pet heal than them, because you don't like chaining pets.  Tell them that giving mages a better heal than theirs is not a threat to their class.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Immlazen:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Anyway to all the Magicians who believe in chaincasting (Epic/No Epic), what would it hurt to have a decent enough heal so you would not have to chain cast.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->What is wrong with the heals we already have?  You have never demonstrated that they are insufficient.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Immlazen:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Hell, why not just give us a regular DOT then, what would we need a pet for?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Well, just off the top of my head, a single cast of elemental with proper healing support, from a cleric say, can deal with 4 mobs at once.  I don't know any dots that can.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Calebe:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  If the heal spell was say 2500 for 450 mana, it is not a complete heal. It is less hit points than a new pet, but it retains it's buffs.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I think <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub115.ezboard.com/feqbeastlordfrm35.showMessage?topicID=2.topic">Sha's Restoration</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> is the best beastlord pet heal at 1250 points for 250 mana.  So you're asking for a spell that heals twice as many hitpoints at a better ratio as the best beastlord pet heal.  And you're not even a priest class.  Well druids get nice nukes, so perhaps it's not as absurd as it looks.<br>
<br>
Now, just as it is foolish to try to eliminate pet chaining as a tactic, likewise it is absurd to force it on mages beyond a few exceptional encounters.  If indeed PoP makes chaining necessary, then it will be necessary to revisit pet heals in order to restore the viability of sustaining pets in PoP encounters.<br>
<br>
Too soon to say, and for now, I've yet to find our existing heals inadequate.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Razamatazz Pizzazz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A> at: 9/30/02 12:38:03 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uimmlazen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Immlazen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 84<br> <font color=#333333>(9/30/02 1:15:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm46.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8.topic&index=78>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Responses</span><hr size=1> Like Ive mentioned before Chaincasting is not my preference.  Also, screw beastlords.  Im not a beastlord.  And I dont see you saying anything about them trading on our territory with some of them wanting better pets.<br>
<br>
Now as I mentioned in another thread.  Why not a decent heal.  Those that want to chaincast can chaincast.  Those that choose to heal their pets can.  You have the option then.  <br>
<br>
The way some Mages on this board is saying...play the way they play or you cant play at all.  Thats bullsh*t.  Ive played the game from 1-60 myself and my tactics evidently worked.  Just because I dont want to use your tactic doesnt mean I cant play.  A decent pet heal will give me a option that I otherwise dont have.  It is a upgrade.  And it doesnt take anything away from those that want to chaincast.  So why are you arguing your point.  Im trying to add something.  Not take anything away.  <br>
<br>
Oh, btw.  You can break that paragraph up any kind of way you want.  That just shows you have to nicpic to make your point stick.  Be original.  Better yet, make your own paragraph.<br>
<br>
Immlazen<br>
Arch Mage <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 1961<br> <font color=#333333>(9/30/02 2:33:23 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm46.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8.topic&index=79>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   The tale of the stubborn archmage...</span><hr size=1> As far as beastlords, yes, and I several other mages are in active discussions on the beastlord forum, sharing what we know about pets and combat, and working towards various proposed solutions to warders that does not infringe on mage and elemental territory.<br>
<br>
Why not a decent heal?<br>
<br>
You are assuming that we need one.  I have yet to see any argument that the heals we have are less than adequate, other than perhaps <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;If I had a super pet heal, then I could fight the same enemies as a pet chainer does, but never chain pets.&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  No argument that a super pet heal is actually necessary for mages, other than your desire to never vary from your favorite tactic, and your insistance that it be adequate for all situations a mage can be expected to handle.<br>
<br>
Let me see if I can explain this another way.<br>
<br>
Suppose an archmage complained that they were spending too much time meditating between fights.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;Have you tried cannibalizing pets?&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> I ask.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;No,&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> they respond, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;I don't like cannibalizing pets.&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  I ask them, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;Have you tried clicking a rod of transvergence when your health gets near full?&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  They respond, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;No, you can't use T-rods without a healer.  Besides, they're not mana regeneration.&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;No,&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the archmage concludes, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;what I need is an upgrade to the phantasmal armor, with mana regeneration more like KEI.&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
How can the archmage's refusal to apply certain tactics be any sort of justification for a super upgrade to TPP?<br>
<br>
It is not.<br>
<br>
Likewise, your refusal to vary from a single tactic in no way justifies a major upgrade to mage pet heals.<br>
<br>
If you are limiting yourself to certain tactics, then you must accept the cost of limiting yourself in that way, and not try to argue that it entitles you to something.<br>
<br>
Why do I argue against some powerful new spell being added to the mage class that we may or may not need?<br>
<br>
Because there might be something else that we really <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>do</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> need.<br>
<br>
Further, a super pet heal that effectively conferred all or most of the advantages of chaining pets to the sustained pet strategy would likely be unbalanced.  Managing aggro would be much easier with the super pet heal than with chaining, and fights would be shorter.  First, because the mage would now be less limited by aggro and therefore free to nuke more often than the chain petter; and second, because the gap between the pets when the new pet is fighting but not yet buffed would go away.<br>
<br>
This new super pet heal would likely destroy chaining as an alternative, being clearly superior, and those mages who invested multiple AA and dozens of hours into a time honored tactic would find that they had wasted all that AA.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;Get your money for nothing, and your exp for free!&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Raz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
